1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper proposes a novel physical layer scheme for MIMO communications based on unsupervised deep learning using an autoencoder. This falls under the domain of information theory, which is concerned with the transmission, processing, and utilization of information. 
2. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper uses deep learning techniques to optimize the physical layer representation and encoding/decoding processes for MIMO communications. This falls under the domain of machine learning, which is concerned with the development of algorithms that can learn from data. 
3. cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing): The paper uses neural networks (specifically, autoencoders) to optimize the MIMO communication system. This falls under the domain of neural and evolutionary computing, which is concerned with the development of algorithms inspired by the structure and function of the brain. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a new system for MIMO communications, which can be adapted for open-loop and closed-loop operation in spatial diversity and multiplexing modes. This falls under the domain of systems and control, which is concerned with the analysis and design of complex systems.
